< Review>
I've tried oggi's twice now, both times take out.

The first time they got one of the three orders wrong and gave me fish and chips instead of a kale chopped salad. It was my mistake not to check before I left but I waited >15 minutes in the restaurant to get it because I was mostly ignored the first 10 minutes while my food sat on the shelf getting cold. I had to re-heat all the hot food when I got home.

I tried them again a couple nights ago thinking maybe my first experience was a fluke. It wasn't. They had a giant white board behind the cash registers that said "there are too many people on this earth. We need a plague." I had to read it twice, like what the hell? Every staff member was staring at screens and seemingly overwhelmed by their job. I waited and waited and no one even looked at me or greeted me. I asked three different people for my take out and each time was told someone else will get it. I could see the bag behind them with my name on it!

I finally got my food after >10 minutes of waiting and was given the wrong change when I paid cash, to be exact I was shorted 90 cents. I paid exact change and should have just received $3 back. Rocket science to that hostess.

Food was ok at best. Cold once again by the time I finally got it.

I won't be trying them again.<//Review>

<Date>1627518711503<//Date><Rating>5</Rating>< review>
Dr. Smoot and his team are awesome! When I first started coming I had recently thrown out my low back. I also had pain between my shoulders blades, in my neck, and also some associated symptoms of migraines as well as hand numbness and tingling. He took X-rays the first visit which showed my low back had actually rotated and that I had a bone spur at the second to last vertebrae in my neck (probably due to computer work and poor posture). The first adjustment was explosive to say the least, but I felt really good afterwards. Now, after about 2 months of treatment, my back and neck pain are minimal, I‚Äôm no longer having migraines or any of the numbness/tingling in my hands. The staff is super friendly, efficient, timely, and are always willing to help. Additionally, Dr. Smoot has a great philosophy of treatment. He explained during the first visit that he aims to actually correct spinal issues when possible and that the treatment goes beyond simply ‚Äúfeeling good.‚Äù Most people start going to a chiropractor when they are in pain and only go maybe once or twice until they improve symptomatically. However, the problem usually recurs soon after and people come back in when they have pain again. The longer treatment plans that he prescribes (plus maintenance work afterwards) are geared to make sure that you stay in good shape long term and prevent any future damage to the spine itself.  I highly recommend coming here if you are seeking chiropractic care!</review>

<Text>Total scam artist. The numerous posters of satisfied patients around the office should have been the first clue. I'm sure they are probably mostly workers comp cases that the patient doesn't have to pay. I went to this office after they were gracious enough to give me a same day appointment. The receptionist are very nice. The reception area has furniture that could use a little upholstery cleaning, but no big deal. After 30 minutes of watching  a video and listening to Dr Smoot talk about himself (another red flag), I should have left. However, he said they were going to 'assess' me and come up with a treatment plan for $220. I assumed this meant I was to be treated. That was not the case. I left $220 shorter with no treatment. They said they would see me the next day and the receptionist said I would be treated then and that would not cost anything. Not true. Day 2: Another video and 30 minutes of Smoot talking about chiropractic theory and then another receptionist coming in saying my 'treatment plan' would cost about $2300 and require about 40 visits over a few months. So let's rewind, I have now had 2 visits, no treatment, paid $220, and they are asking me upfront for another $2300 for a future treatment plan!!!! I expressed my frustration at the fact that I didn't want anything other than an adjustment when I came in the first time. If they could not have provided that for $220 I would have left.They wanted an additional $65 to receive treatment!!!! Don't believe the hype about this guy. < text>
We just moved to Natomas from San Diego and were craving some good Mexican food last night. Dos Coyotes did not disappoint!

I had the cheese enchilada & chicken taco plate. The sauce on the enchilada was flavorful and rich - a perfect compliment to the cheesy goodness within. I opted for a crispy taco and it was not greasy (like some can be), but light, with a definite home made taste. An excellent meal, and the staff were super friendly and welcoming to us as new neighbors. I recommend it!<//text>

< user_name>
Tim Green</user_name>
< Time>
1604474198835<//Time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
My wife and I hired Careful Movers three times: once to unload our moving truck when we moved to California, a second time when we moved from one city to another city in California, and a third time when we moved out of California.

I own a 113-yr-old Steinway piano that is notoriously difficult to move (even compared with other pianos). It has a cast-iron frame and the weight distribution is uneven, both top to bottom and front to back. It also has a rounded bottom, which makes it severely difficult to balance while rolling it on a dolly. This is the only moving company which has been able to move this piano with ease. One of the Careful Movers, Enrique, figured out a way to balance the piano on the dolly (using the wheel cups as wedges), and three or four different professional piano movers we had used before him could not figure out how to do this. While previous movers struggled and cursed trying to move it, and constantly had to keep a man or two to hold the piano up, the Careful Movers crew was able to roll it on a dolly as if it was just any old piano. Enrique and his crew fit the piano into a room in our new place that I honestly did not think would be a possibility. I am a little worried that the next moving company we hire (since we are no longer near Careful Movers) will not be as good and won't be able to get it out.

There are a few other items we own that were on the difficult side for normal professional moving companies to deal with. Nothing terribly unusual (aside from the piano), but just normal difficult stuff. I think the difference with Careful Movers is that they just look at each piece as a puzzle to solve and come up with a creative way to handle it, and they share their solution with you so that you can have an easier move the next time. That alone is worth something.

The quoted estimate was the same as actual cost of each move (no hidden costs). Anthony and his team were great about communicating with me in advance of the move and even fulfilled my request to have the same crew that had moved us before (I only requested this because of the piano), though he was also very clear with me that he couldn't guarantee the same crew.

Additionally, they have always been friendly and professional, and this time around were COVID-safe (wearing masks at all times, even though they are doing heavy lifting. There were no scratches or dents in any of our possessions. They always show up on time and are down to business right away.

I would recommend these guys to anyone in the the SF Bay area whether you're moving to or away. Especially if you have a piano!<//Text>

I'd give this 3.5 stars, but round up to 4.

This is a really cute, family owned, small Turkish spot. They have all kinds of traditional pastries and meals. I got the Turkish breakfast, which looked incredible. It looked a bit better than it tasted, and it was pricy for what it was (sliced tomato, cucumber, salami, and an egg) but the bread was fresh baked and food was satisfying.

I'd probably try it again.<//Review>

I want to love it, but I just can‚Äôt.

Pro: great location, lovely outdoor seating area, friendly staff

Con: food. And drink. I left half of my lukewarm-on-arrival scramble on the plate because the cheese tasted moldy.
I left half of the tea in the cup because the water tastes bad and they don‚Äôt appear to filter it.<//text>

Went to this place as it was somewhat busy, and I ordered the falafel plate. The people there were very nice, and there was water at the side. The seating was either in or outdoor, and we chose a spot outside looking out towards the train tracks. The falafel was great, and the hummus and pita was good too. I would recommend this to anyone who would want Mediterranean food, and they even have a bakery with lots of baked goods.</Text>

<Text>TL;DR: Terrible quality service, cutting corners on hygiene, and incredibly overpriced given this quality.

I've been coming to this place over the last year. Had food here at least 20 times.

Service and food quality was already not great, but it has now gotten to ridiculous levels, so have to give this 1 star.
Today, I found a strange piece of meat (that looked like ham) in a chicken omelette I ordered. I went to the waiting staff to note that, and the only reaction I got was: "Are you sure you didn't order something other than a chicken omelette?", followed by them taking my plate and not saying a single word. Great service guys!

Also: some simple sides (like gozleme, Turkish pancakes) have multiplied 2x in price... with no clear justification.<//Text><pics>None<//pics><resp>None<//resp>< GmapID>

< Text>
If I had to put a label on it, I'd call it a Turkish restaurant, but they also serve crepes and scrambles and other conventional breakfast cafe foods.  The food is very good and reasonably priced. The atmosphere is relaxed and comfortable - food ordering at the counter, order numbers on sticks, indoor and outdoor seating. I'm definitely going back for more.<//Text>

<Name>Yaritza Rodriguez</Name><text>The food is just alright, but the staff is friendly and the place has ample patio seating making it good for hosting families and big groups. It is also a spot one can work out of with plenty of tables and wi-fi so it's not uncommon to find people having lunch meetings and clacking away on weekdays.

Inside there's comfier seating towards the front by the mirror, and a good amount of tables. However, it's not unusual for this area to be highly fragrant with heavy cleaning scents which can compete with the fresh scents of the food and, as is my case, this detail can negatively impact the overall dining experience. If you are not phased by heavy fragrances, it's probably a non-issue for you :)

I still stop by for the occasional chai latte to-go before continuing the rest of my commute, or grab coffee and a snack and work from the patio in warmer weather.< /text></record>

Doughy, raw pastry, undercooked, reheated, doesn't taste fresh, some random parts dry. Not flaky. Greasy, burnt edges & OVERPRICED. things taste STALE and OLD. Mushroom strudel would be better if it had more mushrooms(fresh everything would be nice) and if the pastry was cooked correctly and flaky and not raw on the inside.(AND LESS EXPENSIVE)
Desserts aren't any better, look upscale but are either way too sweet or underwhelming. Creme brulle cheesecake isn't so bad I like the fresh vanilla bean in there but crust is soft and not crunchy and flaky like traditional cheesecake. It's not the right consistency--a little too soft and no signature crunchy scorched sugar on top--its wet and soft.
Entrees are bland and underwhelming, and overcooked. Salmon extremely expensive for being overcooked and not fresh tasting.
Mint lemonade is nice.
All in all tastes like over priced hyped cafeteria food, which is great if you're into that.
They can do so much better for the prices they're charging.
Owners and Chefs....put some effort, buy local and fresh, don't penny pinch, don't freeze and don't overcook/undercook!
Save your money and take a nice drive to another establishment.</review>

<Text>Amazingly delicious juicy baklavas!! They have 3 or 4 different kinds of baklava and basically all of them taste amazing. The price is good and staff is friendly. They have plenty of space outside to enjoy your delicious desserts.

The not so good: I tried their lamb skewers and most of the meat was very chewy that some pieces i just could not breakdown with my teeth ( in the picture my plate looks beautiful though :D ). The salad and rice that came with it was good though. We ordered some falafels and they were not that good--the spices were super strong--We've never tasted falafels with that strong flavor before. Maybe I'll give the meat a second try in the future but for now I'm coming back for their baklava!!</Text>< Pics>

So I gave her $5.00 then told her wait a minute, I have a penny, handed her additional penny (1¬¢) then waited for my change but I didn't get it so I told her "um, change please?" Then she goes "you gave me a penny, what do you think? That I was going to give you a DOLLAR?" What the heck?! That's NO way to talk to ANY customer!

I eat here frequently and I've been very happy with the food and the service. The kaymak and bal is very good, as are many of their savory and sweet pastries. I'm quite fond of the gozleme.

I also appreciate that it's not trying to be fancy or pretentious like many of the new restaurants on Castro. It's just good food.< /Review>

<review>Turkish & Greek dishes + American breakfast + American/Mediterranean cafe entrees & lots of cakes/pastries/desserts. Casual & pleasant cafe atmosphere with outdoor seating (helpful since we often walk there and eat outside with our dog). Service is always pleasant.
I have to confess many dishes are imperfect (for example, I'm always looking for a good breakfast spot; they have a lot of breakfast options, but I find them just OK), but I like some of their items a lot. That plus the service and atmosphere have me coming back often.
I like their desserts, pastries, & paninis. What to get:
- chocolate cake (chocolate cake with chocolate mousse)
- spinach-and-feta gozleme (a savory Turkish pastry...like a filled flaky flatbread)
- chocolate-hazelnut croissant (the croissant is definitely on the very soft side, but it makes me happy enough)
- Athenian Panini (grilled bell pepper, grilled eggplant, tomato, Kalamata olives, provolone)
-Shakshuka
- Capellini Pomodoro (angel hair pasta w/ tomato, basil, olive oil, garlic).
- mint tea< /review><Name>Catherine Nguyen< /Name></record></dataset><record>

< review>
A Turkish bakery and caffe. The service was great, friendly staff, and a great environment. The owner is a nice man from Turkey, he owns a restaurant down the street that we are going to have to check out tomorrow.

We ordered a chocolate chip cookie, and it was massive and delicious, definitely worth the dollar fifty. We also ordered an Acma, which was described to us as a cinnamon roll without the cinnamon. Free hot water and Wi-Fi too, overall great experience. Highly Recommend.

The next day when we stopped by however, we tried to get a cup of hot water to put our tea in, and they tried to make us pay for it, unlike most establishments, which kind of put a dent in the love of the place.<//review>
